Predicting ICU duration

Using the ICU cohort mimiciv_icu_cohort.rds you built in Homework 4, develop at least three machine learning approaches (logistic regression with enet regularization, random forest, boosting, SVM, MLP, etc) plus a model stacking approach for predicting whether a patientâs ICU stay will be longer than 2 days. You should use the los_long variable as the outcome. You algorithms can use patient demographic information (gender, age at ICU intime, marital status, race), ICU admission information (first care unit), the last lab measurements before the ICU stay, and first vital measurements during ICU stay as features. You are welcome to use any feature engineering techniques you think are appropriate; but make sure to not use features that are not available at an ICU stayâs intime. For instance, last_careunit cannot be used in your algorithms.

Feature Engineering

#unique(mimic_icu_cohort$admit_provider_id)

We only use features that are available at an ICU stayâs intime, so we drop last_careunit,dod, outtime ,dischitime,discharge_location and also we have to remove los because it is a target variable. deathtime, edregtime and edouttime are also removed since they have too many missing values. I have also dropped admit_provider_id, since this variable has too many levels and itâs simply the id for people who admitted the patient. I have also dropped anchor_year_group since itâs useless since we have already have the anchor_year.

mimiciv_icu_cohort <- mimic_icu_cohort %>%
  select(-c(last_careunit,dod,los,deathtime,
            edregtime,edouttime, discharge_location,
            outtime, dischtime,
            admit_provider_id, anchor_year_group))

Factor the factor variables

mimiciv_icu_cohort <- mimiciv_icu_cohort %>%

         insurance = factor(insurance),

         gender = factor(gender)

To replace spaces with underscores in all column names

names(mimiciv_icu_cohort) <- gsub(" ", "_", names(mimiciv_icu_cohort))

We also have to convert intime and admittime to a data type that model can process, I have decided to convert them to a three levels factor with the levels being morning, afternoon and night.

convert_time_to_factor <- function(time_column) {
  sapply(time_column, function(time) {
    hour <- as.integer(format(time, "%H"))
    if (hour >= 5 && hour <= 11) {
      return("Morning")
    } else if (hour >= 12 && hour <= 17) {
      return("Afternoon")
    } else {
      return("Night")
    }
  }) -> time_factors
  
  return(factor(time_factors, levels = c("Morning", "Afternoon", "Night")))
}

mimiciv_icu_cohort$intime <- convert_time_to_factor(mimiciv_icu_cohort$intime)
mimiciv_icu_cohort$admittime <- convert_time_to_factor(mimiciv_icu_cohort$admittime)

#3. Train and tune the models using the training set.

Recipe

There are missing values, since missing values are not too much, I would use mean to impute the missing values for the numeric variables and knn method for the categorical variables. As we know, using mean to impute missing values will affect the sample variance. But it also limits the leverage of missing data.

mimic_recipe <-
  recipe(
    los_long ~ .,
    data = Mimic_other
  ) %>%
  step_impute_mean(all_numeric_predictors()) %>%
  step_impute_knn(all_nominal_predictors()) %>%
  step_dummy(all_nominal_predictors()) %>%
  step_zv(all_numeric_predictors()) %>%
  step_normalize(all_numeric_predictors()) %>%
  prep(training = Mimic_other, retain = TRUE)
mimic_recipe %>% bake(Mimic_other)

Model Performance Analysis

Letâs take a look at the feature importance of our models.

We can see form the logistic model that the most important feather is non invasive blood pressure systolic and follow with first_careunit. However, the logistic model didnât perform well in the test set. So we canât trust the feature importance from logistic model.

final_log <- extract_workflow(final_log_fit)
final_log %>% 
  extract_fit_parsnip() %>% 
  vip()

The boosting tree model shows that the most important feather is temperature Fahrenheit and follow with non invasive blood pressure systolic which is also the most important feather in the logistic model. Other important feathers are mainly the the last lab measurements before the ICU stay, and first vital measurements during ICU stay

final_tree <- extract_workflow(final_gb_fit)
final_tree %>% 
  extract_fit_parsnip() %>% 
  vip()

The random forest model shows that the most important feather is heart rate and follow with non invasive blood pressure systolic. However, there are no such big difference between importance of feathers in random forest model. Last lab measurements before the ICU stay, and first vital measurements during ICU stay are still dominate feathers.

final_rf <- extract_workflow(final_rf_fit)
final_rf %>% 
  extract_fit_parsnip() %>% 
  vip()

We have Logistic Regression with Elastic Net Regularization: Accuracy: 0.5837 ROC AUC: 0.6149

Random Forest: Accuracy: 0.6139 ROC AUC: 0.6583

Multilayer Perceptron (MLP): Accuracy: 0.5981 ROC AUC: 0.6309

Boosting: Accuracy: 0.6197 ROC AUC: 0.6653

Model Stacking: ROC AUC: 0.6705

The model stacking approach has the highest ROC AUC, suggesting it may be the best at discriminating between the two classes. Gradient boosting follows closely in terms of ROC AUC and has the highest accuracy among the individual models.

The logistic regression model, while typically more interpretable due to its linear nature and direct coefficient significance, appears to be the least accurate in this case. The MLP shows an ROC AUC that is moderately good, but its accuracy is lower than that of the random forest and boosting models.

From the feature importance analysis, we can see all three models agree that non invasive blood pressure systolic is one of the most important features in predicting long ICU stays. The last lab measurements before the ICU stay and first vital measurements during ICU stay are also in top important features. This suggests that the last lab measurements before the ICU stay and first vital measurements during ICU stay are important indicators of the patientâs condition and may be useful in predicting long ICU stays.

In this case, the trade-off between performance and interpretability is clear. While the model stacking approach gives the best ROC AUC, it does so at the cost of interpretability. On the other hand, logistic regression offers ease of interpretation but doesnât perform as well. The gradient boosting model presents a good balance, with relatively high performance metrics and a degree of interpretability through feature importance scores.
